				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I don't know if the code is working as is, but this:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">LDA (#$00),y</div><br />Has to be changed into this:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">LDA ($00),y</div><br />&quot;#&quot; indicates an immediate value, but this instruction needs an address. Your assembler might be accepting it, but it's wrong so you should change it.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">JoeGtake2 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'm trying to figure out how to append the code to choose where to write the chr information (so, for instance, if I wanted to maintain the first few rows of CHR data but replace the 3rd and 4th...the write would overwrite the data starting there rather than at the beginning).</div><br />your code is currently using a hardcoded source address (myChar) and destination ($0000). What you need to do is make those variable. Ideally you should write a routine that takes a source address, a destination address, and a tile count. There aren't enough registers in the 6502 (A, X and Y only) to specify all that, so you'll either have to pass these parameters through the stack or regular RAM, or build tables describing the blocks that can be copied. For example, a set of tables describing CHR blocks might look like this:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">CHRTileCount:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;.db $40, $08, $10<br /><br />CHRAddressLow:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;.db &lt;MainCharacterTiles, &lt;PowerUpTiles, &lt;EnemyTiles<br /><br />CHRAddressHigh:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;.db &lt;MainCharacterTiles, &lt;PowerUpTiles, &lt;EnemyTiles</div><br />With this you can pass an index to the function that updates the pattern tables in order to tell which CHR block it's supposed to upload. for example:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; &nbsp;ldx #$01<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;lda #$01<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;ldy #$20<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;jsr UpdatePatterns</div><br />With this you can copy 8 power up tiles to PPU address $0120. The subroutine just has to set everything up using these parameters, like this:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">UpdatePatterns:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;sta $2006<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;sty $2006<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;lda CHRTileCount, x<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;sta TileCounter<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;lda CHRAddressLow, x<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;sta $00<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;lda CHRAddressHigh, x<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;sta $01<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;(...)</div><br />And then you can copy bytes like you're already doing, but using X to copy 16 bytes in a loop before decrementing the tile counter and deciding between copying another tile or returning from the function.<br /><br />This is just a suggestion to give you an idea of what can be done, but there are literally thousands of possible solutions, so think carefully about what you're gonna use.<br /><br />EDIT (because of Koitsu's answer): The $2000/$2005 writes should only be necessary to reset the scrolling after you've messed with $2006/$2007, but those are necessary even if you use CHR-ROM, because any PPU write (pattern, name and attribute tables, as well as palettes) messes with $2006/7, not only pattern table updates.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

