				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I would recommend CHR-RAM unless you need to do instantaneous changes. If you can do a quick blackout for your CHR changes, CHR-RAM will do fine. It might take about 8 frames of blackout to update the entire CHR-RAM. If you can't do a blackout, you can upload CHR more slowly in pieces during vblank, but you probably want to at least pause the action while this happens.<br /><br />Here's two reasons you might want CHR-ROM:<br />1. Flipbook animations (e.g. Castlevania gears, or SMB3 dancing world map)<br />2. Paging CHR without any break in gameplay (no brief blackout or pause)<br /><br />You can manage very small CHR animations with CHR-RAM, but since two tiles of CHR is the same amount of data as a whole row of nametable, you can't really update very many tiles on a single frame's vblank. Battletoads is an extreme example that pulls off some very advanced techniques to update two whole character sprites in vblank (in addition to multi-directional scrolling), so depending on how dirty you want to get, you can go pretty far with it.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

