				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sun Jan 22, 2012 12:03 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 2176<br /><b>Location:</b> Canada
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Another bit of advice: the variable TileCounter might be entirely unnecessary if you can just keep this counter in X. Several reasons for this: your tile loading loop doesn't use X for anything else, X is specifically designed for counting (e.g. INX/DEX), the use of a register is faster than going through RAM, and finally it saves space in RAM.<br /><br />If you want it to count tiles, tokumaru pointed out the semantic mismatch between what it's trying to do currently (it's a count of 256 byte chunks?) but you can address that by either changing the stored counts, or even with code<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">LDA chrTileCount, X ; load count of tiles<br />LSR<br />LSR<br />LSR<br />LSR ; A = tile count / 16<br />TAX ; put A into X</div><br /><br />Lastly, and this is probably something you wont want to start doing until later when you're more comfortable with 6502 assembly, but remember that PHA and PLA can be used to store a byte on the stack temporarily. Sometimes this is handy to avoid consuming RAM. It must be used carefully, though, every push needs a corresponding pop, or your program will crash. If you need to store multiple variables temporarily, sometimes the stack is not the best way to go (especially if LIFO access order is not what you need). Anyhow, that's just something to keep in mind for the future, just a bit of a potential optimization technique for when you're further along start to need it.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

